.TH "cicdaemon" "8" "July 14 2026" "cicdaemon 1.1" "CIC Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
.PP
cicdaemon \(en CIC host management and compliance daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
cicdaemon [\f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] [\f[I]SUBSYSTEM OPTION\f[R]]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.TP
\f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] is an orchestrator script that executes a \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] on a hosts given \f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R], like its \f[I]identity\f[R], \f[I]network\f[R], \f[I]dns\f[R], \f[I]time\f[R], \f[I]ssh\f[R], and so on.
Logically, this is similar to something like \f[B]ansible\f[R], except
ansible is too abstraced for me :)
.PP
\f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] may entail \f[I]files\f[R], \f[I]directories\f[R],
\f[I]binaries\f[R], or even connection protocols like \f[B]ssh\f[R](1).
At the end of the day, like \f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] itself,
\f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] are all just \f[B]bash\f[R](1) scripts,
\f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] is just a way to interact with (and make them
interact with each other) easier.
.PP
The difference, however, is that \f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] is able to help the
user (typically an administrator), interpret and reconsile issues in
these subsystems.
While the subsystems by themselves may be able to report on an issue,
that does not necessarily mean it is able to reconsile that issue.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
This setup is mostly for modularity, since it makes it easier to add and
remove scripts.
Better conventions will be implemented as\-needed.
.PP
The \(lqsource of truth\(rq for host configurations is the inventory
file at \f[I]/opt/cicdaemon/inventory.yaml\f[R].
.PD 0
.P
.PD
See \f[B]cicdaemon \-\-help inventory\f[R] for more information.
.PP
If no \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] is specified, \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] defaults to the
\f[B]SUBSYSTEM\f[R]\(cqs \f[I]mode\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Otherwise, \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] defaults to \f[B]show\f[R] or \f[B]ls\f[R],
depending on the context.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
See \f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] and \f[B]SUBSYSTEM MODES\f[R] for more info.
.SH SUBSYSTEMS
A \f[B]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] is a \f[I]logical area of the host you want to
manage\f[R].
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Each subsystem is a smaller \f[B]bash\f[R](1) script that will interact
with the necessary packages, files, directories, etc.
to match the configuration defined at
\f[I]/opt/cicdaemon/config.yaml\f[R].
.PP
Below is the description, valid arguments, and available \f[B]SUBSYSTEM
MODE\f[R] (\f[B]boldface in parenthesis\f[R]) for each subsystem.
.TP
\f[B]show\f[R] [\f[B]active\f[R] | \f[B]all\f[R] | \f[I]subsystem\f[R]]
List \f[B]active\f[R] or \f[B]all\f[R] subsystems, or show details about
a specific \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]init\f[R] [\f[I]subsystem\f[R] \&...] (\f[B]AUDIT\f[R])
Run the \f[B]init\f[R] subsystem on \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
.RS
.PP
\f[B]init\f[R] is effectively the subsystem for subsystems, in which it
checks \f[I]subsystems themselves\f[R], by sourcing the
\f[CR]init()\f[R] function for the \f[I]subsystem\f[R].
The init function for a subsystem typically installs packages, creates
directories, and so on, that the subsystem requires to function.
\f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] itself is a good example of this.
See \f[CR]cicdaemon\-init.sh\f[R] for an example.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]audit\f[R] [\f[I]subsystem\f[R] \&...]
Set \f[I]subsystem\f[R]\(cqs \f[B]mode\f[R] to \f[B]audit\f[R] and run
the \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
.RS
.PP
Similar to \f[B]init\f[R], if no subsystem is specified, default to all
\f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
If \f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] does not have an \f[B]audit\f[R] mode, it will
also be treated as a config error
.RE
.TP
\f[B]enforce\f[R] [\f[I]subsystem\f[R] \&...]
Set \f[I]subsystem\f[R]\(cqs \f[B]mode\f[R] to \f[B]enforce\f[R] and run
the \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]getmode\f[R] [\f[I]active\f[R] | \f[I]all\f[R]] \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
Get the current and possible \f[I]modes\f[R] for \f[I]subsystem\f[R]
.SS SUBSYSTEM MODES
Most subsystems support different \f[I]modes\f[R], depending on what
you\(cqre trying to achieve
.TP
\f[B]init\f[R]
\f[CR]Initialization phase if the subsystem has required packages, directories, etc.\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]audit\f[R]
\f[CR]Read\-only mode. Will print warnings about improper configurations, but won\(aqt attempt to reconcile them\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]enforce\f[R]
\f[CR]Effectively a ripoff from selinux, this will attempt to fix reported issues from subsystems\f[R]
